---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Navbar from '../components/Navbar.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../components/seo/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import JsonLd from '../components/seo/JsonLd.astro';
import LastUpdated from '../components/seo/LastUpdated.astro';
import ScheduleQuiz from '../components/ScheduleQuiz.astro';
import { getCanonicalUrl } from '../lib/seo/metadata';
import { buildBreadcrumbSchema, buildFAQSchema, buildWebPageSchema } from '../lib/seo/schema';

const title = 'Best Custody Schedule for a Teenager | High School, Sports & Parenting Time';
const description =
	'Compare the best custody schedules for teenagers, including week-on/week-off, 50/50, and flexible parenting plans. Includes guidance on driving, sports, jobs, school, and parenting time.';
const canonical = '/best-custody-schedule-for-teenager/';
const canonicalUrl = getCanonicalUrl(canonical);

const breadcrumbs = [
	{ name: 'Home', url: getCanonicalUrl('/') },
	{ name: 'Guides', url: getCanonicalUrl('/blog/') },
	{ name: 'Best Custody Schedule for a Teenager', url: canonicalUrl },
];

const faqItems = [
	{
		question: 'What is the best custody schedule for a teenager?',
		answer:
			'For many teenagers, the best custody schedule is one that protects school, sports, work, friendships, and growing independence while still giving meaningful time with both parents. Week-on/week-off is often a strong starting point because it reduces exchanges and gives teens a full week to manage homework, activities, and transportation from one home. A 5-2-2-5 schedule can work well when parents still want predictable weekday blocks. Customized 50/50 or flexible parenting plans may be better when driving, sports, jobs, or college preparation make a rigid rotation unrealistic. The right choice depends on distance, parent availability, the teen\'s maturity, school demands, and whether both homes can support real-life commitments.',
	},
	{
		question: 'Should teenagers choose where they live?',
		answer:
			'This guide is informational only and is not legal advice. Rules about a teenager\'s preference vary by location and family situation. Practically, many parents give teenagers more input than younger children because teens have school activities, transportation needs, social commitments, jobs, and stronger opinions about daily life. That does not mean a teenager should be placed in charge of adult decisions or asked to choose between parents. A better approach is to ask what is and is not working: long drives, missed practices, lack of quiet study time, social conflicts, or stress around exchanges. A teen\'s input can help parents improve the schedule without making the teen responsible for the custody decision.',
	},
	{
		question: 'Is week-on week-off custody good for teenagers?',
		answer:
			'Week-on/week-off custody can be very effective for teenagers when both homes are organized, reasonably close to school or activities, and able to support the teen\'s routine. The biggest advantage is fewer exchanges. A full week in one home can make it easier to track textbooks, sports gear, laptops, work uniforms, SAT prep, and social plans. The drawback is that a week away from one parent may feel too long for some teens, and it can be difficult if one home is far from school, work, or friends. Week-on/week-off usually works best when the teenager has reliable transportation, a shared calendar, and both parents respect school and activity commitments.',
	},
	{
		question: 'How do sports affect custody schedules?',
		answer:
			'Sports can become one of the biggest drivers of a teenager\'s custody schedule. Varsity teams, club sports, travel teams, conditioning, tournaments, equipment, and weekend games can make a simple custody rotation much harder to follow. Parents need to decide who transports the teen, where equipment is stored, how travel fees are handled, and whether both parents can attend events. A week-on/week-off or customized 50/50 schedule may work better than a frequent-exchange plan because it reduces equipment handoffs. For travel teams, a parenting plan should explain overnight tournaments, missed parenting time, and communication expectations. The goal is not to let sports control the family, but to build a schedule that realistically supports commitments the teen has already made.',
	},
	{
		question: 'How do part-time jobs affect parenting time?',
		answer:
			'Part-time jobs can change teenage custody planning because work shifts often happen during evenings, weekends, and school breaks. A teen who works at a restaurant, grocery store, lifeguard stand, or retail job may need transportation, consistent availability, and enough time for homework. Parents should discuss who drives before the teen has a license, whether work shifts can occur during either parent\'s time, and how missed family time is handled. A rigid every-other-weekend plan can become frustrating if the teen works most weekends. Some families keep the regular overnight schedule but add flexibility for work shifts, meals, or make-up time. The practical question is whether the schedule supports responsibility without turning work into a source of conflict.',
	},
	{
		question: 'Should custody schedules become more flexible during high school?',
		answer:
			'Many custody schedules become more flexible during high school, but flexibility works best when it is structured. Teenagers often have changing responsibilities: sports seasons, exams, jobs, driving practice, social events, college visits, and school projects. A schedule that worked at age 9 may feel too rigid at age 16. Still, a completely informal schedule can create confusion, resentment, and missed parenting time. A better approach is to keep a baseline schedule, such as week-on/week-off, 5-2-2-5, or 60/40, then define how changes are requested and confirmed. Parents can use a custody calendar template to track exceptions and a parenting plan template to describe transportation, notice, and make-up time rules.',
	},
	{
		question: 'How does driving affect custody schedules?',
		answer:
			'Driving can make custody schedules easier, but it also introduces new responsibilities. Once a teenager has a permit or license, exchanges may not require as much parent transportation. The teen may be able to drive to school, practice, work, or a parent\'s home. That can make week-on/week-off, flexible 50/50, or customized schedules more realistic. But parents still need rules about vehicle access, insurance, gas, curfews, passengers, parking, and what happens if the car is unavailable. Driving does not remove the need for a custody plan. It changes the plan from parent-managed transportation to shared responsibility, with adults still setting expectations around safety, school attendance, and communication.',
	},
	{
		question: 'What custody schedule works best for a teenager preparing for college?',
		answer:
			'A teenager preparing for college may need a schedule that protects study time, applications, essays, visits, interviews, scholarships, and extracurricular commitments. Week-on/week-off can work well because it creates longer blocks for focused schoolwork and fewer exchanges. A flexible 50/50 or customized 60/40 schedule may be better if one home is closer to school, tutoring, work, or college-prep activities. Parents should agree who tracks application deadlines, test registration, financial aid forms, college visits, and recommendation letters. The best schedule is usually the one that reduces chaos during an already demanding season. A custody schedule generator can show the weekly pattern, but a parenting plan should cover college-prep responsibilities in writing.',
	},
	{
		question: 'Can siblings have different custody schedules?',
		answer:
			'Siblings can have different custody schedules when their ages, schools, activities, or needs are very different. A toddler may need routine and frequent contact, a 7-year-old may need homework support, and a teenager may need flexibility around driving, sports, work, and social life. Keeping siblings together can be emotionally helpful and simpler for parents, but forcing one schedule on every child can create problems when a teenager has late practices or a job. Some families keep the same overnight homes but allow the teenager more flexibility for activities and transportation. The goal is to avoid making the calendar so complicated that no one can follow it while still respecting each child\'s stage of life.',
	},
	{
		question: 'What if a teenager refuses to follow the custody schedule?',
		answer:
			'If a teenager refuses to follow the custody schedule, parents should avoid turning the issue into a power struggle when possible. This guide is not legal advice, and existing orders matter, but practically the first step is to understand why the teen is resisting. Common reasons include long drives, missing friends, conflict in one home, lack of privacy, activity conflicts, work schedules, or feeling treated like a younger child. Parents can ask specific questions and look for practical changes: fewer exchanges, better transportation, more study space, clearer curfews, or a flexible parenting plan. If safety, court orders, or serious conflict are involved, parents may need professional or legal guidance.',
	},
	{
		question: 'What is the best custody schedule for a 13-year-old?',
		answer:
			'A 13-year-old is often entering middle school, building stronger friendships, and becoming more involved in activities. The best schedule usually balances structure with a little more flexibility than younger children need. 5-2-2-5 can work well because it creates predictable weekday blocks while keeping regular contact with both parents. Week-on/week-off may work for mature 13-year-olds who handle longer blocks and stay organized with school supplies. Parents should pay attention to sports, clubs, social invitations, and screen-time routines. A 13-year-old may want input, but adults still need to manage transportation, homework expectations, and communication between homes.',
	},
	{
		question: 'What is the best custody schedule for a 15-year-old?',
		answer:
			'A 15-year-old may have heavier schoolwork, sports, dating, a learner permit, volunteer hours, or early job responsibilities. Week-on/week-off often becomes more realistic at this age because fewer exchanges can reduce disruption and the teen may be better at managing supplies. A customized 50/50 schedule can also work if activities and transportation require flexibility. Parents should plan for driving practice, insurance discussions, school events, and weekend commitments. A strict schedule that ignores the teen\'s real calendar may create avoidable conflict. The best plan keeps both parents involved while recognizing that high school responsibilities are becoming part of the custody equation.',
	},
	{
		question: 'What is the best custody schedule for a 17-year-old?',
		answer:
			'A 17-year-old often needs a custody schedule that looks more like a transition plan into young adulthood. School, work, driving, dating, college applications, internships, senior-year events, and friendships may dominate the calendar. Week-on/week-off, flexible 50/50, or a customized plan may work better than frequent exchanges. Parents should focus on maintaining meaningful relationships while supporting responsibility and future planning. The schedule may need rules for cars, curfews, overnight events, college visits, work shifts, and graduation activities. A 17-year-old may have strong preferences, but the healthiest plans usually combine teen input with clear adult expectations.',
	},
];

const ageComparisonRows = [
	['Toddler', 'Attachment, naps, bedtime, and short separations.', '/best-custody-schedule-for-toddler/', 'Toddler custody guide'],
	['5-Year-Old', 'Kindergarten routine, school readiness, and frequent contact.', '/best-custody-schedule-for-5-year-old/', '5-year-old custody guide'],
	['7-Year-Old', 'Homework, school activities, friendships, and predictable weekdays.', '/best-custody-schedule-for-7-year-old/', '7-year-old custody guide'],
	['Teenager', 'Independence, driving, activities, jobs, social life, and future planning.', '/best-custody-schedule-for-teenager/', 'Current guide'],
];

const teenAgeRows = [
	{
		age: '13-Year-Old',
		focus: 'Middle school, friendships, clubs, sports, phones, and more independent routines.',
		considerations: 'Keep structure clear, but start listening to practical preferences about activities, friends, and schoolwork.',
	},
	{
		age: '15-Year-Old',
		focus: 'High school workload, varsity or club sports, learner permits, dating, and greater independence.',
		considerations: 'Plan around transportation, driving practice, activity schedules, and whether fewer exchanges reduce stress.',
	},
	{
		age: '17-Year-Old',
		focus: 'Jobs, driving, college applications, senior-year events, dating, and transition into adulthood.',
		considerations: 'Use a flexible but written plan that supports school, work, future planning, and meaningful time with both parents.',
	},
];

const scheduleRows = [
	{
		title: 'Week-On Week-Off',
		href: '/week-on-week-off-custody-schedule/',
		pros: 'Simple calendar, fewer exchanges, and longer blocks for homework, sports, work, and social plans.',
		cons: 'A full week away from one parent can feel too long, and each home must fully support school and activities.',
		bestFor: 'Organized teenagers, high school schedules, nearby homes, and families that want fewer handoffs.',
		avoid: 'Avoid it when the teen needs more frequent parent contact or one home is far from school, work, or activities.',
	},
	{
		title: '5-2-2-5',
		href: '/5-2-2-5-custody-schedule/',
		pros: 'Predictable weekday blocks with equal parenting time over two weeks.',
		cons: 'More exchanges than week-on/week-off and more coordination around activities and transportation.',
		bestFor: 'Younger teens or families wanting equal time while keeping recurring weekdays consistent.',
		avoid: 'Avoid it when practices, work shifts, or social commitments make midweek exchanges difficult.',
	},
	{
		title: '50/50 Custody',
		href: '/50-50-custody-schedule/',
		pros: 'Balanced parenting time with room to customize around driving, activities, and school.',
		cons: 'A pure percentage goal can become unrealistic if it ignores the teen\'s actual commitments.',
		bestFor: 'Both parents live close, both support the teen\'s commitments, and the teen can handle transitions.',
		avoid: 'Avoid rigid 50/50 when distance, work, sports, or school demands make the plan stressful.',
	},
	{
		title: '60/40',
		href: '/60-40-custody-schedule/',
		pros: 'One home can anchor more school nights while the other parent keeps substantial time.',
		cons: 'One parent may have less ordinary weekday involvement unless the plan protects meaningful contact.',
		bestFor: 'Distance, demanding activities, school transportation issues, or one parent with more availability.',
		avoid: 'Avoid using it only for convenience if a balanced plan works well and supports the teenager.',
	},
	{
		title: 'Every Other Weekend',
		href: '/every-other-weekend-custody-schedule/',
		pros: 'Fewer exchanges and simpler school-week logistics when distance or conflict is a major factor.',
		cons: 'Can feel too limited for a teenager who wants ordinary time with both parents.',
		bestFor: 'Long distance, limited availability, high conflict, or situations where school-week exchanges do not work.',
		avoid: 'Avoid it as a default if both parents are nearby and the teen wants regular involvement with both homes.',
	},
];

const scenarioRows = [
	{
		title: 'Scenario 1: Teen athlete',
		challenge: 'A 16-year-old has varsity practice after school, weekend games, and summer conditioning.',
		recommendation: 'Week-on/week-off or flexible 50/50 with written sports transportation rules.',
		reasoning: 'Fewer exchanges reduce gear handoffs, and both parents can plan around practices, games, and travel.',
	},
	{
		title: 'Scenario 2: Teen with a part-time job',
		challenge: 'A 15-year-old works Friday evenings and some Sunday afternoons.',
		recommendation: 'Customized 50/50 or 60/40 that protects work shifts and homework time.',
		reasoning: 'The schedule should support responsibility without turning every weekend shift into a parenting-time conflict.',
	},
	{
		title: 'Scenario 3: Teen preparing for college',
		challenge: 'A 17-year-old has SAT prep, college visits, essays, and scholarship deadlines.',
		recommendation: 'Week-on/week-off or flexible parenting plan with clear college-prep responsibilities.',
		reasoning: 'Longer blocks and fewer handoffs can protect focus while both parents remain involved in planning.',
	},
	{
		title: 'Scenario 4: Parents live 45 minutes apart',
		challenge: 'The commute affects school arrival, practices, and social plans.',
		recommendation: '60/40, every other weekend, or a custom plan with fewer school-week exchanges.',
		reasoning: 'Less frequent travel may be healthier than forcing equal time that disrupts school and activities.',
	},
	{
		title: 'Scenario 5: Teen already drives',
		challenge: 'A licensed teen can transport themselves but needs rules around cars, gas, curfew, and parking.',
		recommendation: 'Flexible 50/50 or week-on/week-off with vehicle and communication rules.',
		reasoning: 'Driving can reduce parent transportation burdens, but adults still need clear expectations.',
	},
	{
		title: 'Scenario 6: High-achieving student with many commitments',
		challenge: 'The teen balances AP classes, music, debate, volunteering, and a demanding social calendar.',
		recommendation: 'Flexible parenting plan anchored by a predictable baseline schedule.',
		reasoning: 'Structure prevents chaos, while flexibility lets the teen meet real school and activity obligations.',
	},
];

const calendarExamples = [
	{
		title: 'Week-On Week-Off Example',
		weekOne: ['A', 'A', 'A', 'A', 'A', 'A', 'A'],
		weekTwo: ['B', 'B', 'B', 'B', 'B', 'B', 'B'],
		note: 'Best when the teen can handle longer blocks and both homes can support school, activities, and transportation.',
	},
	{
		title: '5-2-2-5 Example',
		weekOne: ['A', 'A', 'A', 'A', 'A', 'B', 'B'],
		weekTwo: ['A', 'A', 'B', 'B', 'B', 'B', 'B'],
		note: 'Useful when parents want equal time but still need predictable weekday blocks.',
	},
	{
		title: 'Flexible 50/50 Example',
		weekOne: ['A', 'A', 'A', 'B', 'B', 'A', 'A'],
		weekTwo: ['B', 'B', 'A', 'A', 'B', 'B', 'B'],
		note: 'Works best when the pattern is written down but adjusted for sports, jobs, driving, and major school events.',
	},
];

const tools = [
	{ title: 'Custody Schedule Generator', href: '/custody-schedule-generator/', description: 'Create a teen custody calendar with real dates, exchanges, and school-year patterns.' },
	{ title: 'Custody Calendar Template', href: '/custody-calendar-template/', description: 'Track sports, jobs, school events, college visits, holidays, and parenting time.' },
	{ title: 'Custody Percentage Calculator', href: '/custody-percentage-calculator/', description: 'Estimate parenting-time percentages for 50/50, 60/40, and custom teen schedules.' },
	{ title: 'Parenting Time Calculator', href: '/parenting-time-calculator/', description: 'Compare overnights and parenting time across different schedule options.' },
	{ title: 'Parenting Plan Template', href: '/parenting-plan-template/', description: 'Write down driving, jobs, curfews, school, activities, and communication rules.' },
	{ title: 'Custody Schedule Template', href: '/custody-schedule-template/', description: 'Build a printable schedule for school-year, summer, and flexible teen parenting time.' },
];

const schema = [
	buildFAQSchema(faqItems),
	buildBreadcrumbSchema(breadcrumbs),
	{
		...buildWebPageSchema({ name: title, description, url: canonicalUrl }),
		dateModified: '2026-06-11',
		isAccessibleForFree: true,
		about: [
			'best custody schedule for a teenager',
			'teen custody schedule',
			'week-on week-off custody for teenagers',
			'50/50 custody schedule for teenager',
			'parenting plan for teenager',
		],
	},
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} canonical={canonical}>
	<JsonLd slot="head" data={schema} />
	<Navbar />
	<Breadcrumbs items={breadcrumbs} />
	<main>
		<section class="container-shell py-10 lg:py-14">
			<div class="premium-card rounded-[2rem] p-6 lg:p-8">
				<p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-muted">Custody schedules by age</p>
				<h1 class="mt-4 max-w-4xl text-5xl font-semibold leading-[0.98] tracking-[-0.055em] text-primary lg:text-6xl">
					Best Custody Schedule for a Teenager
				</h1>
				<LastUpdated />
				<div class="mt-6 grid gap-4 text-base leading-8 text-secondary lg:grid-cols-[1.15fr_0.85fr]">
					<div class="grid gap-4">
						<p>
							Teenagers often need custody schedules that balance school, sports, friendships, part-time jobs, driving, social life, and growing independence. A schedule that worked for a toddler or elementary-school child may feel too rigid once a child enters the teenage years.
						</p>
						<p>
							Many families gradually become more flexible as children become teenagers. The goal is not to let the calendar disappear. The goal is to keep enough structure for parents while giving the teenager room to manage real commitments.
						</p>
						<p>
							The best custody schedule for a teenager is usually the one that supports ordinary teen life: homework, practices, work shifts, friends, transportation, college preparation, and meaningful relationships with both parents.
						</p>
					</div>
					<div class="soft-card rounded-[1.5rem] p-5 text-sm leading-6">
						<p class="font-semibold text-primary">Educational note</p>
						<p class="mt-2 text-secondary">
							This guide is informational only and is not legal advice. Custody decisions should account for safety, existing orders, school needs, the teenager, parent availability, and local guidance when needed.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="mt-8 flex flex-col gap-3 sm:flex-row">
					<a href="/custody-schedule-generator/" class="btn-primary inline-flex h-12 w-full items-center justify-center rounded-full px-7 text-sm font-semibold sm:w-auto">Build a Teen Custody Schedule</a>
					<a href="#schedule-options" class="btn-secondary inline-flex h-12 w-full items-center justify-center rounded-full px-7 text-sm font-semibold sm:w-auto">Compare teen schedules</a>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="container-shell py-section">
			<div class="premium-card rounded-[2rem] p-6 lg:p-8">
				<p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-muted">Practical recommendation</p>
				<h2 class="mt-3 text-4xl font-semibold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Our Practical Recommendation</h2>
				<div class="mt-5 grid gap-6 lg:grid-cols-[1.1fr_0.9fr]">
					<div class="grid gap-4 text-base leading-8 text-secondary">
						<p>
							For many teenagers, the strongest first choice is a <a href="/week-on-week-off-custody-schedule/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">week-on/week-off schedule</a>. It reduces exchanges, gives each home a full school week, and can make sports, jobs, homework, and transportation easier to manage.
						</p>
						<p>
							A <a href="/5-2-2-5-custody-schedule/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">5-2-2-5 schedule</a> can work well for younger teens or families who want equal time but still need repeated weekday blocks. A <a href="/50-50-custody-schedule/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">customized 50/50 schedule</a> or flexible parenting plan may be best when driving, sports, work, or college prep changes the calendar often.
						</p>
						<p>
							Teen custody planning should not be only about percentages. It should account for independence, transportation, school commitments, social life, and whether the teenager can realistically keep up with responsibilities across two homes.
						</p>
					</div>
					<div class="soft-card rounded-[1.5rem] p-5">
						<p class="text-sm font-semibold text-primary">Best first comparison</p>
						<ol class="mt-3 grid gap-2 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary">
							<li>1. Week-on/week-off for fewer exchanges and longer blocks.</li>
							<li>2. 5-2-2-5 for predictable equal-time weekdays.</li>
							<li>3. Customized 50/50 for activities, driving, and jobs.</li>
							<li>4. Flexible parenting plans for older high school students.</li>
						</ol>
						<a href="/custody-schedule-generator/" class="btn-primary mt-5 inline-flex h-11 items-center justify-center rounded-full px-5 text-sm font-semibold">Generate a teen schedule</a>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<ScheduleQuiz title="Find a Starting Custody Schedule for Your Teenager" ageGroup="teen" />

		<section class="container-shell py-section">
			<div class="grid gap-6 lg:grid-cols-[0.8fr_1.2fr]">
				<div>
					<p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-muted">Teenage custody planning</p>
					<h2 class="mt-3 text-4xl font-semibold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Why Custody Planning Changes During the Teenage Years</h2>
					<p class="mt-4 text-base leading-7 text-secondary">
						Teenagers are no longer only moving between homes. They are moving between school, practice, work, friends, driving lessons, exams, and future plans.
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2">
					{[
						['Independence', 'Teens may manage more of their own time, but parents still need shared expectations.'],
						['Social life', 'Friends, dating, dances, parties, and school events start shaping the calendar.'],
						['School commitments', 'High school work, exams, projects, and college prep require reliable study time.'],
						['Sports and activities', 'Varsity teams, clubs, band, theater, and travel teams can dominate evenings and weekends.'],
						['Jobs', 'Part-time work adds evening and weekend obligations that younger children do not have.'],
						['Transportation', 'Permits, licenses, cars, insurance, and gas can change how exchanges happen.'],
					].map(([heading, text]) => (
						<article class="soft-card rounded-[1.5rem] p-5">
							<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold tracking-[-0.03em] text-primary">{heading}</h3>
							<p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary">{text}</p>
						</article>
					))}
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="mt-6 overflow-x-auto rounded-[1.5rem] border border-line bg-surface shadow-[0_18px_44px_rgba(15,23,42,0.06)]">
				<table class="min-w-[800px] w-full text-left text-sm">
					<thead class="bg-surface-elevated text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.16em] text-muted">
						<tr><th class="px-4 py-3">Age</th><th class="px-4 py-3">Main Custody Focus</th><th class="px-4 py-3">Recommended Reading</th></tr>
					</thead>
					<tbody class="divide-y divide-line text-secondary">
						{ageComparisonRows.map(([age, focus, href, label]) => (
							<tr><td class="px-4 py-4 font-semibold text-primary">{age}</td><td class="px-4 py-4">{focus}</td><td class="px-4 py-4"><a href={href} class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">{label}</a></td></tr>
						))}
					</tbody>
				</table>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="container-shell py-section">
			<div class="premium-card rounded-[2rem] p-6 lg:p-8">
				<h2 class="text-4xl font-semibold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Custody Considerations by Teen Age</h2>
				<div class="mt-6 grid gap-4 lg:grid-cols-3">
					{teenAgeRows.map((row) => (
						<article class="soft-card rounded-[1.5rem] p-5">
							<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.03em] text-primary">{row.age}</h3>
							<p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary"><span class="font-semibold text-primary">Focus:</span> {row.focus}</p>
							<p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary"><span class="font-semibold text-primary">Schedule considerations:</span> {row.considerations}</p>
						</article>
					))}
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section id="schedule-options" class="container-shell py-section">
			<div class="max-w-3xl">
				<p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-muted">Schedule options</p>
				<h2 class="mt-3 text-4xl font-semibold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Best Custody Schedules for Teenagers</h2>
				<p class="mt-4 text-base leading-7 text-secondary">
					For teenagers, the schedule should be judged by how well it supports independence, school, activities, transportation, work, and social life.
				</p>
			</div>
			<div class="mt-6 grid gap-4 lg:grid-cols-2">
				{scheduleRows.map((schedule) => (
					<article class="soft-card rounded-[1.5rem] p-5">
						<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.03em] text-primary"><a href={schedule.href} class="hover:text-accent">{schedule.title}</a></h3>
						<div class="mt-4 grid gap-2 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary">
							<p><span class="font-semibold text-primary">Pros:</span> {schedule.pros}</p>
							<p><span class="font-semibold text-primary">Cons:</span> {schedule.cons}</p>
							<p><span class="font-semibold text-primary">Best for:</span> {schedule.bestFor}</p>
							<p><span class="font-semibold text-primary">When to avoid:</span> {schedule.avoid}</p>
						</div>
					</article>
				))}
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="container-shell py-section">
			<div class="premium-card rounded-[2rem] p-6 lg:p-8">
				<div class="grid gap-6 lg:grid-cols-[0.9fr_1.1fr]">
					<div>
						<p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-muted">Transportation shift</p>
						<h2 class="mt-3 text-4xl font-semibold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">How Driving Changes Custody Schedules</h2>
						<p class="mt-4 text-base leading-7 text-secondary">
							Driving can be the biggest practical change in teenage custody planning. Once a teen has a learner permit or license, the calendar may become less dependent on parent-to-parent handoffs.
						</p>
					</div>
					<div class="grid gap-4 text-sm leading-7 text-secondary">
						<p>
							A licensed teenager may be able to drive to school, practice, work, or the other parent\'s home. This can make <a href="/week-on-week-off-custody-schedule/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">week-on/week-off</a> or flexible 50/50 easier because the teen is not waiting for every ride.
						</p>
						<p>
							But driving adds questions: Who provides the vehicle? Who pays insurance? Can the teen drive siblings? Who pays gas? What happens if the car is unavailable? Are there passenger, curfew, or weather rules?
						</p>
						<p>
							For example, a 16-year-old who drives may spend the school week with one parent but stop by the other parent\'s home for dinner after practice. A 17-year-old may drive to a weekend shift and then return to the scheduled parent\'s home. Driving creates flexibility, but the expectations still need to be written down.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="container-shell py-section">
			<div class="grid gap-6 lg:grid-cols-2">
				<div class="soft-card rounded-[1.75rem] p-6">
					<h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Sports, Activities, and Travel Teams</h2>
					<div class="mt-4 grid gap-3 text-sm leading-7 text-secondary">
						<p>Teen commitments can include varsity sports, club teams, travel tournaments, marching band, theater, debate, music, robotics, tutoring, and volunteer hours.</p>
						<p>The custody plan should define transportation, equipment storage, overnight travel, missed parenting time, fees, and communication. A travel tournament may affect both parents even if it falls during one parent\'s weekend.</p>
						<p>For activity-heavy teens, a <a href="/custody-calendar-template/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">custody calendar template</a> can prevent last-minute confusion about practices, games, rehearsals, and school events.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="soft-card rounded-[1.75rem] p-6">
					<h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">How Part-Time Jobs Affect Custody Planning</h2>
					<div class="mt-4 grid gap-3 text-sm leading-7 text-secondary">
						<p>Many custody guides ignore part-time jobs, but work schedules can reshape teenage parenting time. Weekend shifts, evening work, summer jobs, and transportation can conflict with ordinary custody blocks.</p>
						<p>A teen working Friday nights may need flexibility in an every-other-weekend schedule. A teen without a license may need a clear transportation plan. A teen with a license may need car, gas, curfew, and communication rules.</p>
						<p>The best plan supports responsibility without letting work erase parent-child time. Some families add make-up dinners, shared rides, or flexible blocks around known shifts.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="container-shell py-section">
			<div class="grid gap-6 lg:grid-cols-2">
				<div class="soft-card rounded-[1.75rem] p-6">
					<h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Friends, Dating, and Social Events</h2>
					<p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-7 text-secondary">
						Teenagers often care deeply about sleepovers, dating, dances, parties, school events, and social circles. A schedule that looks perfect on paper may create unnecessary friction if it constantly interrupts social commitments.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-7 text-secondary">
						Parents do not need to approve every event, but they should avoid making the teenager negotiate adult custody issues to attend normal teen activities. A clear calendar and consistent communication rules help.
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="soft-card rounded-[1.75rem] p-6">
					<h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Should Teenagers Have a Say in the Schedule?</h2>
					<p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-7 text-secondary">
						Teenagers often have useful information about what is not working: long drives, missed practices, lack of privacy, school stress, friend conflicts, or feeling over-scheduled. Parents can listen without asking the teen to choose between homes.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-7 text-secondary">
						Input should be balanced with maturity, safety, school obligations, and parent cooperation. A teenager can help improve the plan, but adults should still carry the responsibility for structure and final decisions.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="container-shell py-section">
			<div class="premium-card rounded-[2rem] p-6 lg:p-8">
				<div class="grid gap-6 lg:grid-cols-[0.85fr_1.15fr]">
					<div>
						<p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-muted">High school planning</p>
						<h2 class="mt-3 text-4xl font-semibold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">School Success and College Preparation</h2>
					</div>
					<div class="grid gap-4 text-sm leading-7 text-secondary">
						<p>
							High school custody schedules should support grades, SAT or ACT preparation, college applications, essays, scholarship deadlines, extracurricular commitments, and time management.
						</p>
						<p>
							Parents should decide who tracks college visits, application deadlines, tutoring, financial aid forms, and school meetings. A teen may be mature, but college preparation still requires adult organization.
						</p>
						<p>
							A flexible plan can help during exam weeks or application season. The baseline schedule matters, but the real value is reducing chaos so the teenager can focus on school and future goals.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="container-shell py-section">
			<h2 class="text-4xl font-semibold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Real Family Scenarios</h2>
			<div class="mt-6 grid gap-4">
				{scenarioRows.map((scenario) => (
					<article class="soft-card rounded-[1.5rem] p-5">
						<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.03em] text-primary">{scenario.title}</h3>
						<div class="mt-4 grid gap-3 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary md:grid-cols-3">
							<p><span class="font-semibold text-primary">Challenge:</span> {scenario.challenge}</p>
							<p><span class="font-semibold text-primary">Recommendation:</span> {scenario.recommendation}</p>
							<p><span class="font-semibold text-primary">Reasoning:</span> {scenario.reasoning}</p>
						</div>
					</article>
				))}
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="container-shell py-section">
			<div class="grid gap-6 lg:grid-cols-[0.85fr_1.15fr]">
				<div>
					<h2 class="text-4xl font-semibold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">What Parents of Teenagers Often Get Wrong</h2>
					<p class="mt-4 text-base leading-7 text-secondary">Teen custody problems often come from treating a high school student like a younger child.</p>
				</div>
				<ul class="grid gap-3 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary sm:grid-cols-2">
					<li class="soft-card rounded-2xl p-4">Prioritizing the schedule label over daily practicality.</li>
					<li class="soft-card rounded-2xl p-4">Ignoring sports, clubs, work shifts, and social commitments.</li>
					<li class="soft-card rounded-2xl p-4">Creating unnecessary exchanges that interrupt school or activities.</li>
					<li class="soft-card rounded-2xl p-4">Failing to adapt as the teenager becomes more mature.</li>
					<li class="soft-card rounded-2xl p-4">Expecting the teen to manage adult communication between homes.</li>
					<li class="soft-card rounded-2xl p-4">Treating driving as freedom without setting car, safety, and curfew rules.</li>
				</ul>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="container-shell py-section">
			<div class="grid gap-6 lg:grid-cols-2">
				<div class="soft-card rounded-[1.75rem] p-6">
					<h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Why Many Teen Custody Schedules Become More Flexible</h2>
					<p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-7 text-secondary">
						Flexibility does not mean the schedule becomes vague. It means the family keeps a baseline plan while allowing reasonable changes for exams, games, work shifts, dances, college visits, and transportation.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-7 text-secondary">
						For teenagers, consistency is still important. The difference is that consistency may come from clear rules for changing the calendar, not from forcing every week to look identical.
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="soft-card rounded-[1.75rem] p-6">
					<h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Warning Signs a Schedule Needs Adjustment</h2>
					<ul class="mt-4 grid gap-2 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary">
						<li>Constant transportation conflicts.</li>
						<li>Repeated missed practices, jobs, school events, or social commitments.</li>
						<li>School performance or sleep declines.</li>
						<li>The teen feels excessive stress around exchanges.</li>
						<li>Driving, car access, or curfew rules are unclear.</li>
						<li>The schedule creates conflict every time activities change.</li>
					</ul>
					<p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary">These signs do not automatically mean the custody schedule is wrong, but they suggest the family should review logistics, flexibility, and communication.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="container-shell py-section">
			<div class="max-w-3xl">
				<p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-muted">Calendar examples</p>
				<h2 class="mt-3 text-4xl font-semibold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Visual Calendar Examples</h2>
				<p class="mt-4 text-base leading-7 text-secondary">
					Use these examples to compare exchange frequency, longer home blocks, and room for sports, jobs, driving, and school commitments.
				</p>
			</div>
			<div class="mt-6 grid gap-5">
				{calendarExamples.map((example) => (
					<article class="soft-card rounded-[1.5rem] p-5">
						<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.03em] text-primary">{example.title}</h3>
						<div class="mt-4 overflow-x-auto rounded-[1.25rem] border border-line bg-surface">
							<table class="min-w-[560px] w-full text-left text-sm">
								<thead class="bg-surface-elevated text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.14em] text-muted">
									<tr><th class="px-3 py-3">Week</th><th class="px-3 py-3">Mon</th><th class="px-3 py-3">Tue</th><th class="px-3 py-3">Wed</th><th class="px-3 py-3">Thu</th><th class="px-3 py-3">Fri</th><th class="px-3 py-3">Sat</th><th class="px-3 py-3">Sun</th></tr>
								</thead>
								<tbody class="divide-y divide-line text-secondary">
									<tr><td class="px-3 py-3 font-semibold text-primary">Week 1</td>{example.weekOne.map((day) => <td class="px-3 py-3">Parent {day}</td>)}</tr>
									<tr><td class="px-3 py-3 font-semibold text-primary">Week 2</td>{example.weekTwo.map((day) => <td class="px-3 py-3">Parent {day}</td>)}</tr>
								</tbody>
							</table>
						</div>
						<p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary">{example.note}</p>
					</article>
				))}
			</div>
			<p class="mt-5 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary">Generate your own version with real dates using the <a href="/custody-schedule-generator/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">Custody Schedule Generator</a>.</p>
		</section>

		<section class="container-shell py-section">
			<div class="premium-card rounded-[2rem] p-6 lg:p-8">
				<h2 class="text-4xl font-semibold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Which Schedule Is Best for Your Family?</h2>
				<div class="mt-6 grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2">
					{[
						['Choose week-on/week-off if...', ['The teen handles longer blocks well', 'Fewer exchanges help school or activities', 'Both homes support high school routines', 'Transportation is manageable'], '/week-on-week-off-custody-schedule/'],
						['Choose 5-2-2-5 if...', ['The teen is younger', 'Predictable weekdays matter', 'Parents want equal time', 'Midweek exchanges are not disruptive'], '/5-2-2-5-custody-schedule/'],
						['Choose 50/50 if...', ['Both parents live close', 'The teen wants regular time with both homes', 'Activities are supported by both parents', 'The plan can be customized'], '/50-50-custody-schedule/'],
						['Choose 60/40 if...', ['One home is closer to school or activities', 'Distance makes equal time stressful', 'One parent has more school-week availability', 'The other parent still has meaningful time'], '/60-40-custody-schedule/'],
						['Choose every other weekend if...', ['Distance is substantial', 'One parent has limited availability', 'The teen has major school-week commitments', 'Holidays and summer can add time'], '/every-other-weekend-custody-schedule/'],
					].map(([heading, items, href]) => (
						<a href={href} class="soft-card group rounded-[1.5rem] p-5 transition-all duration-200 hover:-translate-y-0.5 hover:border-accent/40">
							<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.03em] text-primary">{heading}</h3>
							<ul class="mt-3 grid gap-2 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary">{items.map((item) => <li>{item}</li>)}</ul>
						</a>
					))}
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="container-shell py-section">
			<div class="premium-card rounded-[2rem] p-6 lg:p-8">
				<h2 class="text-4xl font-semibold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">What Parents of Teens Often Underestimate</h2>
				<div class="mt-6 grid gap-4 text-sm leading-7 text-secondary md:grid-cols-2">
					<p>Transportation becomes a major issue. Even after a teen drives, cars, insurance, gas, parking, curfews, and backup rides still need rules.</p>
					<p>Activities can dominate the schedule. Sports, clubs, jobs, and school events may matter more than the exact custody percentage.</p>
					<p>Social life matters more than many parents expect. A plan that repeatedly blocks friends, dances, or school events may create avoidable conflict.</p>
					<p>Practical schedules often outperform perfect schedules. A flexible plan that parents can follow may work better than an elegant rotation that fails every week.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="container-shell py-section">
			<h2 class="text-4xl font-semibold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Child Custody Schedules by Age</h2>
			<p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-base leading-7 text-secondary">Age does not decide custody by itself, but it changes what the schedule needs to protect.</p>
			<div class="mt-6 overflow-x-auto rounded-[1.5rem] border border-line bg-surface shadow-[0_18px_44px_rgba(15,23,42,0.06)]">
				<table class="min-w-[760px] w-full text-left text-sm">
					<thead class="bg-surface-elevated text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.16em] text-muted"><tr><th class="px-4 py-3">Age</th><th class="px-4 py-3">Main Focus</th><th class="px-4 py-3">Recommended Reading</th></tr></thead>
					<tbody class="divide-y divide-line text-secondary">
						{ageComparisonRows.map(([age, focus, href, label]) => (
							<tr><td class="px-4 py-4 font-semibold text-primary">{age}</td><td class="px-4 py-4">{focus}</td><td class="px-4 py-4"><a href={href} class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">{label}</a></td></tr>
						))}
					</tbody>
				</table>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="container-shell py-section">
			<div class="premium-card rounded-[2rem] p-6 lg:p-8">
				<h2 class="text-4xl font-semibold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Helpful Custody Planning Tools</h2>
				<div class="mt-6 grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2 xl:grid-cols-3">
					{tools.map((tool) => (
						<a href={tool.href} class="soft-card group rounded-[1.5rem] p-5 transition-all duration-200 hover:-translate-y-0.5 hover:border-accent/40">
							<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold tracking-[-0.03em] text-primary">{tool.title}</h3>
							<p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary">{tool.description}</p>
							<span class="mt-4 inline-flex text-sm font-semibold text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 group-hover:text-primary">Open tool</span>
						</a>
					))}
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section id="faq" class="container-shell py-10 lg:py-12">
			<div class="max-w-3xl">
				<p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-muted">FAQ</p>
				<h2 class="mt-3 text-4xl font-semibold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Questions About Custody Schedules for Teenagers</h2>
			</div>
			<div class="mt-6 grid gap-3">
				{faqItems.map((item) => (
					<details class="soft-card group rounded-[1.35rem] p-5">
						<summary class="cursor-pointer list-none text-base font-semibold text-primary">{item.question}</summary>
						<p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-7 text-secondary">{item.answer}</p>
					</details>
				))}
			</div>
		</section>
	</main>
	<Footer />
</BaseLayout>
